[2]
Date: Fri, 23 Apr 2004 19:49:05 +0800
From: Jack Soo <kyip@gmx.net>
Source: China MOH website press release [Trans. by Jack Soo]
<http://www.moh.gov.cn/zhgl/zt/yqfb/1200404230004.htm>

Cases of [atypical pneumonia] in Anhui and Beijing; experts [suspect]
source may be lab infection
--------------------------------------------------
A medical department news spokesperson confirmed that the medical expert
group has identified] a [case of atypical pneumonia infection] in Anhui
Province and that [Beijing province also has a case of atypical pneumonia].
[The patient in] Anhui, is a 26 year old [woman], Anhui medical college
master graduate student. During the period 7--22 March she was studying in
the Chinese Viral disease control laboratory and on 23 Mar 2004 she took
the train to return to Hefei, Anhui. On 25 Mar 2004 she developed fever and
took the train back from Anhui to Beijing. On 29 Mar 2004 she underwent a
medical examination, was found to have pneumonia and was admitted to
hospital at the [?Beijing Healthy Palace] hospital. On 2 Apr 2004 she took
the train to return to Anhui Huai Nan for treatment. On 4 Apr 2004 she was
transferred to the Anhui Medical College for continued treatment of viral
pneumonia. Beginning 31 Mar 2004, her mother continuously cared for and
accompanied her and provided nursing care.
On 8 Apr 2004 [her mother] developed a fever and was admitted to hospital
in the Anjui Medical College Hospital with viral pneumonia. On 19 Apr, her
mother worsened and died. Upon receipt of notification of this death by the
local medical department, the early warning mechanism was activated. On 21
Apr 2004, the Anhui Province Disease Control center had IgG positive blood
tests [for SARS Co-V], this was reexamined by the Jiangsu Province Disease
Control Center which also had IgM and IgG seropositivity.
On the evening of 21 Apr 2004, the Anhui Province Health Department
reported the findings to the Medical Department. On the morning of 22 Apr
2004, the Medical Department expert group rushed to Anhui. On 23 Apr 2004
the China Center for Disease Control senate compared the laboratory tests
(IgG and IgM findings). The medical department expert group reviewed the 2
patients clinical courses/presentations, the laboratory examinations and
the epidemiologic investigation and [confirmed] the diagnosis of atypical
pneumonia in the index case from Anhui [the graduate student] and referred
autopsy specimens for confirmation on the index case's mother.
Anhui Province has conducted strict disinfection of the areas of the 2
patients and has identified 117 close contacts of these 2 patients. At
present, the index case is stable, and one of her close contacts has
developed fever.
Further investigation revealed that in Beijing on 22 Apr 2004 there was a
report of a case of atypical pneumonia that is epidemiologically linked to
the index case in Anhui. The case in Beijing, a nurse, cared for the index
case from Anhui during the period 29 Mar to ? Apr when the patient was in
the Healthy Palace Hospital in Beijing. Given the epidemiologic linking of
the 2 patients, Beijing has classified the case in Beijing as a case of
atypical pneumonia [SARS] infection. Currently the case in Beijing is
afebrile. Of 188 close contacts of this case in Beijing, 5 have fever. 3 of
these 5 are close relatives of the Beijing case and 2 are from the hospital
contacts at the Earth Temple Hospital (one a patient and one a visitor
caring for a patient).
On 23 Apr 2004, Beijing reported another case of atypical pneumonia (SARS).
This patient is a 31 year old man, doing postdoctoral work at the China
Center for Disease Control Viral Disease laboratory. On 17 Apr [???], on 22
Apr 2004 he was admitted to the Earth Temple Hospital. On review of his
clinical and epidemiologic history, Beijing immediately classified him as a
case of atypical pneumonia [SARS].
In view of the fact that the index patient in Anhui and the patient from
Beijing both worked in the China Center for Disease Control viral
laboratory the epidemiological investigation is pointing towards the
laboratory as the source of infection and further investigations among the
laboratory staff are in process. The Medical Department has sealed the
China Center for Disease Control Viral laboratory and is investigating the
personnel, obtaining laboratory specimens from sampling within the
laboratory. Safety control measures are being investigated and implemented.
The medical department has requested the fever monitoring be conducted
under supervision [of laboratory staff?]. The medical department has
reported to the World Health Organization and to Hong Kong. The Red Cross
Society of China has reported this to the Taiwan Red Cross.
--
Jack Soo
<kyip@gmx.net>
