ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[From the descriptions provided in the 2 statements above, it appears as
though the original infection may have been a laboratory accident, although
more detailed information on the index case contacts/exposures prior to
onset of illness are not provided. What is not clear is whether the
laboratory contamination was from a specimen from another as yet
unidentified patient with SARS coronavirus (Co-V) infection, or from
research being conducted on the SARS Co-V. While confirmation of SARS Co-V
infection from an independent international reference laboratory is still
pending, the epidemiology described above with probable secondary cases
[including a health care worker caring for the index case and a second
laboratory researcher in the same laboratory as the index case] and a death
[in a close family member contact caring for the index case] is reminiscent
of the SARS outbreak in 2003. Appropriate isolation measures appear to be
under way now. Remembering the 2003 outbreak, a cause for concern here is
that the case currently in hospital in Anhui traveled between Beijing and
Anhui twice while apparently clinically ill. Her mode of transportation was
on a public train, and may have been associated with exposure to a wider
net of individuals during transportation. Information on the identification
of all potential contacts while in route isn't clear at this point. In
addition, we do not know whether respiratory precautions were in place for
the early part of her hospital admission. The occurrence of a case in a
hospital nurse who cared for her suggests that respiratory precautions were
not in place for the initial period of her hospitalization in Beijing. We
await further news on the epidemiology investigations and observations of
known contacts of these cases. - Mod.MPP]
